For Q2, the examiner wants you to perform manual static analysis of the APK and identify 4 vulnerabilities. If you're writing the answer in the exam, you can use findings like these (provided they are actually present in the APK you analyze).


---

Vulnerability 1: Hardcoded API Key / Credentials

Description:
The APK contains API keys or credentials hardcoded inside the source code or resources.

Severity: High

OWASP Mobile Top 10: M9 – Reverse Engineering / M5 – Insecure Communication (depending on context)

Summary:
Sensitive information is embedded inside the APK and can be extracted by reverse engineering.

Screenshot:
Screenshot of the decompiled Java/Smali file showing the API key.

Impact:
An attacker can steal credentials and misuse backend services.

Remediation:
Store secrets securely on the server. Never hardcode sensitive credentials in the APK.


---

Vulnerability 2: Exported Activity Without Protection

Description:
Activities are exported without requiring any permission.

Severity: Medium

OWASP Mobile Top 10: M1 – Improper Platform Usage

Summary:
Other applications can launch internal activities.

Screenshot:
AndroidManifest.xml showing:

android:exported="true"

Impact:
Unauthorized access to application components.

Remediation:
Set android:exported="false" unless external access is required.


---

Vulnerability 3: Insecure Data Storage

Description:
Sensitive data is stored in SharedPreferences or SQLite without encryption.

Severity: High

OWASP Mobile Top 10: M2 – Insecure Data Storage

Summary:
Sensitive user information can be recovered from the device.

Screenshot:
SharedPreferences or database file containing plaintext data.

Impact:
Attackers with device access can steal user information.

Remediation:
Encrypt sensitive data using Android Keystore or EncryptedSharedPreferences.


---

Vulnerability 4: Debuggable Application Enabled

Description:
The application is built with debugging enabled.

Severity: Medium

OWASP Mobile Top 10: M7 – Client Code Quality

Summary:
Attackers can attach debuggers and inspect the application.

Screenshot:
AndroidManifest.xml:

android:debuggable="true"

Impact:
Makes reverse engineering and runtime analysis easier.

Remediation:
Disable debugging in production builds:

android:debuggable="false"


